he Qing Empire's policy of controlling Manchuria and Choson Korea. Kim also contributes to theKorean history of the Choson dynasty (1392-1910) by challenging conventional accounts that embrace a China-centered interpretation of the tributary relationship between the two polities, stressing instead the agency of Choson Korea in the formation of the Qing Empire. This study demonstrates how Koreans interpreted and employed this relationship in order to preserve the boundary-and peace-with the suzerain power. By focusing on the historical significance of the China-Korea boundary, this book defines the nature of the Qing Empire through the dynamics of contacts and conflicts under both the cultural and material frameworks of its tributary relationship with Choson Korea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aBorderlandszChinaxHistory. 0aBorderlandszKoreaxHistory. 0aGinseng. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a17th to 19th century.  aasian history.  achinese.  achoson dynasty.  achoson korea.  acountry boundaries.  ahistorical significance.  ainternational relations.  akorean history.  akorean.  amanchu history.  amanchu qing dynasty.  amanchu.  anew qing history.  apeace.  apolitical relations.  aqing china.  asouth korean history.  astate boundaries.  asuzerain power.  aterritorial boundaries.  atribal state.  atributary relationship.  auniversal empire.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968714zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520968714.jpg  a978-3-11-06